### Military bases

York County is, rather significantly, home to several large and strategically vital military facilities belonging to the [United States](/United_States). These installations, positioned along the [York River](/York_River_(Virginia)), even have small, almost apologetic, portions extending into the adjacent [James City County](/James_City_County,_Virginia). The military, it seems, rarely respects arbitrary lines on a map.

The [Coast Guard Training Center Yorktown](/Coast_Guard_Training_Center_Yorktown) is one such prominent fixture.

The [Naval Weapons Station Yorktown](/Naval_Weapons_Station_Yorktown) was originally established during the throes of [World War I](/World_War_I), by direct order of President [Woodrow Wilson](/Woodrow_Wilson). It has since expanded to incorporate the formerly separate Cheatham Annex Supply Complex, a testament to its ever-growing logistical importance. [Camp Peary](/Camp_Peary), another significant installation, was brought into existence during [World War II](/World_War_II) initially as a [Seabee](/Seabee_(US_Navy)) Training Base, churning out skilled naval construction workers. As the war progressed, its strategic value shifted, and it became an invaluable, highly secretive facility for housing sensitive prisoners-of-war captured from German naval vessels. It was deemed absolutely critical that Nazi authorities remain unaware of their capture, particularly because it suggested that secret code books, previously thought lost at sea, might have been compromised. Many of these former POWs, perhaps finding a strange comfort in their new surroundings, chose to make Virginia and the [United States](/United_States) their new homeland after the cessation of hostilities. Separating these two colossal military reservations is [Queen's Creek](/Queen%27s_Creek), a natural waterway that originates in the western reaches of the county and gracefully drains into the [York River](/York_River_(Virginia)), a subtle reminder that nature persists, even amidst military might.

York County has, over its long history, seen the disappearance of several communities, including the rather generically named Yorke. The establishment of these sprawling military reservations in the first half of the 20th century led to the absorption of a substantial number of small towns. These include the original [Lackey](/Lackey,_Virginia) (known affectionately, or perhaps resignedly, as "the Reservation"), [Halstead's Point](/Halstead%27s_Point,_Virginia), [Penniman](/Penniman,_Virginia), [Bigler's Mill](/Bigler%27s_Mill,_Virginia), and [Magruder](/Magruder,_Virginia). The displaced residents and their descendants, many of whom were farmers and watermen—professions inextricably linked to the land and sea—now find themselves residing in places such as [Yorktown](/Yorktown,_Virginia), [Gloucester](/Gloucester_County,_Virginia), [Lee Hall](/Lee_Hall,_Virginia), [Grove](/Grove,_Virginia), and [Lightfoot](/Lightfoot,_Virginia). A testament to human adaptability, or perhaps, simply a lack of better options.

